# "REAL SOFTWARE SURVIVES ABUSE."

"CSS Crime Scene: A website from the old internet that looks like it was assembled by someone who hated visual alignment but understood the human condition. Often more alive than modern polished sludge."

"Placeholder pile-on is the gradual burial of a project beneath layers of stubs, temporary workarounds, planned features, empty interfaces, and future promises until the visible structure becomes much larger than the working system underneath.A fake-out. It creates the appearance of momentum and completeness while making it increasingly difficult to distinguish what is real, what is unfinished, and what only exists as an intention.Self-deception, and what's worse, a balm that deters real progress. " 

"Cardboard code is code that looks functional and convincing until it encounters the conditions real software must survive. It depends on ideal inputs, ideal environments, ideal timing, and ideal users, often lacking the resilience, validation, recovery, observability, and failure handling needed to withstand reality. Like a cardboard building on a movie set, it presents the shape of a solution witthout possessing the strength of one."

"Spec Lust:The lust to make hardware confess. Not “I own big specs,” but “watch what I forced the specs to do.” Spec Lust is when a man sees 64GB RAM and does not think “capacity.” He thinks “unspent violence.” It is not hardware ownership. It is hardware interrogation."

"Minimalistic Maximmalism: The doctrine that the system should be brutally small where it rests and brutally huge where it works. Minimal surface. Maximal output. No wasted daemons. No mystery sludge. No little background goblins eating RAM under the floorboards."

"Outline-Legible Engineering: The discipline of making a project understandable from its visible shape. Folder names, module names, command names, and README sections should tell the truth before anyone opens a file. If a stranger cannot understand at least half the project from the outline, the repo is wearing a fake mustache."

"By the Laws of Physics: The final blessing. The point where the Min-Maxer has profiled, shaved, aligned, cached, batched, and spiritually threatened the program until there is nowhere left to go. If he says “literally it can’t go faster by the laws of physics,” he has either reached truth or needs sleep. Usually both."

"Unearned Complexity:Complexity that did not win its citizenship. A tool bringing a colosseum to hammer a nail. A dependency stack so tall birds nest in it. A system that needs six services to remember a wallpaper. The Min-Maxer does not hate complexity. He hates complexity that showed up without receipts."

"Mystery Sludge:Any unexplained performance, memory, or architecture mess. “It’s just slow for some reason” is mystery sludge. “The app needs 2GB RAM to open a settings panel” is mystery sludge in formalwear. The Min-Maxer exists to point at it until somebody cries or profiles it."



"Cognitive Sludge: The wet mental fog caused by vague names, bloated folders, and files called manager.c, helpers.c, stuff.c, or real_final_use_this_one.c. Cognitive sludge is what happens when a codebase makes your brain put on wet socks."

"Sleeper Stack Ascension is the dream of taking a modest machine, giving it small, strategic hardware upgrades, then pairing those upgrades with a brutally optimized open-source software stack until it starts beating “better” modern computers in specific categories."

"Min-Max: The street name for Minimalistic Maximalism. Shorter, nastier, more usable in public. “I’m on that Min-Max stuff” means the speaker has probably optimized something nobody asked him to optimize and is waiting for society to thank him later."

"Min-Maxer: The worst man in the thread, and unfortunately, the one who is probably right. He asks about cold cache when everyone else is celebrating. He has the social texture of sandpaper and the emotional timing of a smoke alarm. At first you hate him. Later your dataset grows. Then you understand."

"Benchmark Goblin: A creature who cannot see a number without wanting another number beside it. He says “just curious” before producing twelve logs, a CSV, a graph, and a small theology of filesystem behavior. His avatar is a low-resolution penguin wearing sunglasses."

"Shape Before Detail:The principle that the system’s visible outline should carry meaning before implementation is studied. The tree is the first diagram. The module names are labels on the machinery."

"Repo Shape: The first confession of a codebase. Before anyone reads the code, they see the tree. A good repo shape says, “I know what I am.” A bad repo shape says, “There was a lot going on emotionally.”" 

"Mystery Sludge:Any unexplained performance, memory, or architecture mess. “It’s just slow for some reason” is mystery sludge. “The app needs 2GB RAM to open a settings panel” is mystery sludge in formalwear. The Min-Maxer exists to point at it until somebody cries or profiles it."

